Then she slipped down among the flower- pots on the other side of the tubs and stood, hanging her head. 
"Natdsha," he said, "you know that I love you, but . . ." 
"You are in love with me?" Natdsha broke in. 
"Yes, I am, but please don't let us do like that. ... In another four years . . . then I will ask for your hand." 
Natasha considered. 
"Thirteen, fourteen, fifteen, sixteen," she counted on her slender little fingers. "All rightl Then it's settled?"
